<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-247-798  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 247 798.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  May 8 1989 v6 n18 p16(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Adobe program to share fonts over network. (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kovsky, Steven.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Users and manufacturers of workstations and microcomputers will beable to purchase software packages for scalable font technologyfrom Adobe Systems Inc. Adobe Type Manager will allow commontypefaces to be shared by different computer architectures acrossa network.andP;  Outline fonts will generate characters forhigher-quality screen displays, and printers will share the sametechnology.andP;  All but 2 percent of network traffic for outputtingbit-mapped text will be eliminated by the font technology.andP;  Thepackage can work with Adobe's Display PostScript technology, whichallows manipulation of text and integration of graphics which ATMcannot achieve alone.andP;  The Apple Macintosh was the only platformannounced for ATM, although Display PostScript is not licensed forthe Mac.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Adobe Systems Inc. (product introduction).andO;Ticker:    ADBE.andO;Product:   Type Manager (Printer software) (product introduction)Display PostScript (Printer software) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Software PackagesFontsNetworksProduct Introduction.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Adobe Program To Share Fonts over NetworkandM;MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif.andP;  -- Adobe Systems last week introduced a scalable fonttechnology that it will sell to users and manufacturers of workstations andPCs.andM;Executives of the $83 million software company said the debut of Adobe TypeManager next fall will allow different computer architectures to share commontypefaces over a network.andM;Essentially, the type manager program will reside in RAM on a desktopmachine, using Adobe outline fonts to generate characters on the screen.andO;Adobe officials said the software will provide higher-quality screen displaysthat more closely resemble printed output.andM;Adobe will also license the type manager technology to printer manufacturers.andM;With printers and desktop machines both running the type manager program, itwill no longer be necessary to send complex bit-mapped information from thecomputer to the printer, according to Adobe executives.andM;As a result, a coded ASCII file will be sent to the printer, where it will betranslated back into bit-mapped fonts.andP;  This system will eliminate all but 2percent of the network traffic now necessary to output bit-mapped text,according to Adobe President Charles Geschke.andM;The type manager software also meshes with computers that use Adobe's DisplayPostscript technology, such as DEC hardware, Geschke said.andM;Ellen Nold, Adobe's product marketing manager, said DEC is among the firstDisplay PostScript licensees to begin shipping products that use the pagedescription system.andP;  Display PostScript is supported now in any hardwarerunning DECwindows, Nold said.andM;The only announced platform of Adobe Type Manager is the Apple Macintosh.andO;Adobe executives said they expect to port the software to other platforms,but would not discuss likely candidates.andM;John Warnock, Adobe's chairman and chief executive officer, admitted thatAdobe has no agreement with Apple concerning the use of the type manager, andAdobe's plans to retail the product could put that company in competitionwith future Apple font-description software products.andM;Apple has not licensed Display PostScript for its Macintosh PCs.andM;Adobe Type Manager software handles only typeface information.andP;  The DisplayPostScript system allows for more complex manipulations of typefaces and addsthe ability to integrate graphics and images with text, company officialssaid.andM;Adobe declined to release pricing for the new product.andM;For more information, Adobe Systems Inc. can be contacted at 1585 CharlestonRoad, Mountain View CA 94039-79000, (415) 961-4400.andO;</TEXT></DOC>